{"title_page": "Wet market", "text_new": "{{Short description|Market selling perishable goods, generally including meat or food animals}}\n{{Chinese|pic=WetmarketHK.jpg|picsize=250px|c=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]|j=gaai<sup>1</sup> si<sup>5</sup>|l=street market|showflag=j|ci={{IPAc-yue|g|aai|1|.|s|i|5}}}}\n<!-- \"\u8857\u5e02\" only means \"wet market\" in Cantonese, so pinyin here is unnecessary -->\n\nA '''wet market''' (also called a '''public market''')<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/> is a [[marketplace]] selling fresh meat, fish, [[greengrocer|produce]], and other perishable goods as distinguished from \"dry markets\" that sell durable goods such as fabric and electronics.<ref>Wholesale Markets: Planning and Design Manual (Fao Agricultural Services Bulletin) (No 90)</ref><ref name=\"OED\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/227970 |title=wet, adj. |publisher=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |quote=wet market  n. South-East Asian a market for the sale of fresh meat, fish, and produce  |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Wet markets are common throughout the world.<ref name=\"nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/peta-launches-petition-close-wet-markets-coronavirus-1494803 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |title= PETA LAUNCHES PETITION TO SHUT DOWN LIVE ANIMAL MARKETS THAT BREED DISEASES LIKE COVID-19 |first=Khaleda |last=Rahman |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reardon|first=Thomas|last2=Timmer|first2=C. Peter|last3=Minten|first3=Bart|date=2012-07-31|title=Supermarket revolution in Asia and emerging development strategies to include small farmers|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=109|issue=31|pages=12332\u201312337|doi=10.1073/pnas.1003160108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3412023|pmid=21135250|bibcode=2012PNAS..10912332R}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800725826/why-wet-markets-are-the-perfect-place-to-spread-disease|title=Why Wet Markets Are The Perfect Place To Spread Disease|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Wet markets include a wide variety of markets, such as [[farmers' market]]s, [[fish market]]s, and [[Wildlife trade|wildlife market]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/>\n\nWet markets containing live animals, both domesticated and wild, as well as wildlife products have been linked to outbreaks of [[zoonotic disease]]s including [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\":2\" /> However, not all wet markets carry living animals or wildlife.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /> Wet markets were  banned from holding wildlife in China in 2003, including after the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], which was directly tied to such practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> Such regulations were lifted before being put into place again in 2020,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/74f1b26e-53c0-11ea-90ad-25e377c0ee1f|title=Coronavirus piles pressure on China\u2019s exotic animal trade|last=Yu|first=Sun|last2=Liu|first2=Xinning|date=2020-02-23|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> with other countries following suit.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eba067c4-69ce-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3|title=The economic case for ending wildlife trade hits home in Vietnam|last=Reed|first=John|date=2020-03-19|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nMedia reports that fail to distinguish between wet markets from those with live produce or wildlife have been blamed for fueling [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobia related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"FP\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/coronavirus-covid19-dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-virus/ |publisher=[[Foreign Policy]] |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Coronavirus |last=Palmer |first=James |date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe \"wet\" in \"wet market\" refers to the constantly wet floors as a consequence of the spraying of fresh produce and cleaning of meat and seafood stalls.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiFxfmZteFgC |title=Cross-Cultural Marketing: Theory, Practice and Relevance |first=Dawn |last=Burton |page=146 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2008|isbn=9781134060177 }}</ref>\n\nAs early as 1948, \"wet market\" was identified as a name in English for a type of market.<ref name=\"IRCD\">{{cite web|url=https://northeastiowarcd.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IA-FM-Chapter-1.pdf |publisher=Northeast Iowa Resource Conservation & Development |title=Chapter 1: What is a Farmer's Market? |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> The term \"wet market\" originated from [[Hong Kong English]] and entered the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 May 2016 |title=East Asian words make it into ''Oxford English Dictionary'' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/13/east-asian-words-oxford-english-dictionary-hong-kong-singapore-oed |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date=22 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe term \"public market\" is synonymous with \"wet market\",<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/> although it may sometimes refer exclusively to state-owned and community-owned wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/>\n\n==Types of wet markets==\nThe term \"wet market\", which specifies markets that sell fresh produce and meat, include a broad variety of markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\">{{Cite journal |last=Zhong |first=Taiyang |last2=Si |first2=Zhenzhong |last3=Crush |first3=Jonathan |last4=Scott |first4=Steffanie |last5=Huang |first5=Xianjin |year=2019 |title=Achieving urban food security through a hybrid public-private food provisioning system: the case of Nanjing, China |journal=Food Security |language=en |volume=11 |issue=5 |pages=1071\u20131086 |doi=10.1007/s12571-019-00961-8 |issn=1876-4517}}</ref> Wet markets can be categorized according to their ownership structure ([[Privately held company|privately owned]], [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned]], or [[Community ownership|community-owned]]), scale ([[Wholesaling|wholesale]] or [[retail]]), and produce (vegetables, slaughtered meat, live animals).<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/> They can be further subcategorized based on whether the meat sold comes from [[Domestication of animals|domesticated]] or [[wildlife|wild animal]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/>\n\n==Economy==\nWet markets are less dependent on imported goods than [[supermarket]]s due to their smaller volumes and lesser emphasis on consistency.<ref name=\"ATH-12\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=12}}</ref> Researchers have highlighted the lower prices, greater freshness of food, negotiation opportunities, and social interaction spaces as key reasons for the persistence of wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bougoure |first=Ursula |last2=Lee |first2=Bernard |year=2009 |editor-last=Lindgreen |editor-first=Adam |title=Service quality in Hong Kong: wet markets vs supermarkets |journal=British Food Journal |language=en |volume=111 |issue=1 |pages=70\u201379 |doi=10.1108/00070700910924245 |issn=0007-070X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Mele |first=Christopher |last2=Ng |first2=Megan |last3=Chim |first3=May Bo |year=2015 |title=Urban markets as a 'corrective' to advanced urbanism: The social space of wet markets in contemporary Singapore |journal=Urban Studies |language=en |volume=52 |issue=1 |pages=103\u2013120 |doi=10.1177/0042098014524613 |issn=0042-0980}}</ref>\n\nThe persistence of wet markets has been described as \"critical for ensuring urban [[food security]]\",<ref name=\"Morales-2009\">{{Cite journal |last=Morales |first=Alfonso |year=2009 |title=Public Markets as Community Development Tools |journal=Journal of Planning Education and Research |language=en |volume=28 |issue=4 |pages=426\u2013440 |doi=10.1177/0739456X08329471 |issn=0739-456X}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2011\">{{Cite journal |last=Morales |first=Alfonso |year=2011 |title=Marketplaces: Prospects for Social, Economic, and Political Development |journal=Journal of Planning Literature |language=en |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=3\u201317 |doi=10.1177/0885412210388040 |issn=0885-4122}}</ref> particularly in Chinese cities.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/> The influence of wet markets on urban food security include food pricing and physical accessibility.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/>\n\n==Wet markets by country==\n=== China ===\n[[File:Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market, Hall 1 (20190519152946).jpg|thumb|Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market in [[Beijing]], [[China]]]]\nThe origin of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in [[Wuhan]], [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/prevention-and-screening-articles/wuhan-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: What we know so far about the 2019 novel coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, proposals were made to ban the operation of wet markets selling wild animals for human consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-feb-17-2020-1.5466207/experts-call-for-global-ban-on-live-animal-markets-wildlife-trade-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-1.5466219|title=Experts call for global ban on live animal markets, wildlife trade amidst coronavirus outbreak|date=February 17, 2020|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|author=Sarah Boseley}}</ref> A few others have pointed out that most wet markets in China do not sell wild animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/wet-markets-wild-animals-china/|title=No, You Won't Find \"Wild Animals\" in Most of China's Wet Markets|last=Bossons|first=Matthew|date=2020-02-25|website=RADII|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last=Lynteris|first=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market was shut down on 1 January 2020. The Chinese government subsequently announced a permanent ban on the sale of wild animal products at wet markets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/china-bans-wildlife-trade-consumption-coronavirus-2020-2|publisher=Business Insider|date=25 February 2020|title=China just banned the trade and consumption of wild animals. Experts think the coronavirus jumped from live animals to people at a market.|author=Aylin Woodward}}</ref> By {{date|2020-04-02|DMY}}, some temporarily closed wet markets in China were reported to have been reopened, leading to public criticism of the Chinese government's handling of wild animal trade by [[Anthony Fauci]] and [[Lindsey Graham]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'reilly|first=Andrew|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/lindsey-graham-asks-china-to-close-all-operating-wet-markets-after-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Lindsey Graham asks China to close 'all operating wet markets' after coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-04-02|work=Fox News|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowden|first=John|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490834-graham-asks-colleagues-to-support-call-for-china-to-close-wet-markets|title=Graham asks colleagues to support call for China to close wet markets|date=2020-04-02|work=The Hill|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Fauci\"/>\n\n==== Hong Kong ====\n[[File:HK Bridges Street Market.JPG|thumb|The building that housed the former [[Bridges Street Market]] in [[Hong Kong]]]]\nIn 1920, the Reclamation Street Market was opened in [[Hong Kong]]. Due to structure problems, Reclamation Street Market was removed by the government in 1953.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c46\u5eff\u4e00\u4e16\u7d00\u83ef\u4eba\u5730\u5340\u6b77\u53f2\u6559\u80b2\u8ad6\u6587\u96c6|trans-title=Second Collection of Historical Education Papers on Chinese in the 21st Century |author=Bao Shaolin|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (Hong Kong) Limited.|year=2012|language=Chinese|isbn=|location=|pages=332}}</ref> In 1957, Yau Ma Tei Street Market launched to replace the Reclamation Street Market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmis.hkpl.gov.hk/coverpage/-/coverpage/view?p_r_p_-1078056564_c=QF757YsWv59a9PNz3lScYjii24oro5jB&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_o=18&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_actual_q=%28%20%28%20allTermsMandatory%3A%28true%29%20OR+all_dc.title%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.creator%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.contributor%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.subject%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+fulltext%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.description%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20%29%20%29&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_order=desc&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_field=score&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_log=Y|title=\u6cb9\u9ebb\u5730\u65b0\u5efa\u8857\u5e02\u6628\u6668\u958b\u5e55\u5f8c\u71df\u696d|trans-title=Yau Ma Tei New Market opened after opening yesterday morning|language=Chinese|last=|first=|date=1957-11-02|work=Hong Kong Business Daily|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There were fixed-pitch stalls which sold vegetables, fruits, seafood, beef, pork, and poultry. Also, there were stalls selling baby chickens, baby ducks, and three-striped box turtles as pets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkmemory.hk/collections/oral_history/All_Items_OH/oha_70/records/index.html|title=Yau Ma Tei's wet markets in the early post-war period|date=2011-03-29|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref><br />\n\nCentral Market was launched on 16 May 1842. Its position was central, on Queen's Road. In this market, people could find all kinds of meat, fruit and vegetables, poultry, salt fish, fresh fish, weighing rooms and money changers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1842/728468.pdf|title=The Friend Of China, and Hong Kong Gazette|date=1842-05-12|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn Hong Kong, wet markets are most frequented by older residents, those with lower incomes, and domestic helpers who serve approximately 10 percent of Hong Kong's residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1412265&show=abstract |title=EmeraldInsight |website=EmeraldInsight.com |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Wet markets have become destinations for tourists to \"see the real Hong Kong\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/a-guide-to-hong-kongs-wet-markets/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Sei | last=Chong | title=A Guide to Hong Kong's Wet Markets | date=18 March 2011|accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Many of the wet market buildings are owned by property investment firms and as a result the price of food can vary from market to market.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elmer W. Cagape |url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/64501/expensive-food-tung-chung-hk/ |title=Tung Chung town pays the most for food in Hong Kong |work=Asian Correspondent |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, wet markets accounted for 70% of produce sales and 50% of meat sales in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"ATH-7\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the government of Hong Kong proposed that all poultry should be slaughtered at central abattoirs to combat the spread of [[avian flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.news.gov.hk/isd/ebulletin/en/category/issues/080614/html/080613en05005.htm |title=Central abattoir set for 2011 |website=Archive.news.gov.hk |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nHong Kong's wet markets use red lampshades to make the food look fresher.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u8d85\u5de8\u8857\u5e02\u71c8\u73fe\u8eab\u5546\u5834|trans-title=Super large wet market red lamps appears in shopping mall|url=http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Sharp Daily|date=14 September 2012|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108070308/http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\n[[File:Mercado 20 de noviembre - Oaxaca de Ju\u00e1rez - 10.jpg|thumb|Fresh meat section of the Mercado 20 de Noviembre in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], [[Mexico]]]]\nSome traditional [[Mexico|Mexican]] open-air markets called ''[[tianguis]]'', such as the Mercado Margarita Maza de Ju\u00e1rez in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], are separated into a wet market (''zona h\u00fameda'') and a dry market (''zona seca'').<ref name=\"imparcial\">{{cite news |url=https://imparcialoaxaca.mx/oaxaca/304648/central-de-abasto-bomba-de-tiempo-y-nido-de-delincuencia/ |title=Central de Abasto: bomba de tiempo y nido de delincuencia |publisher=[[El Imparcial (Oaxaca)]] |date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\nIn the early 1990s, the slaughter of animals was banned in 12 inner-city markets and 22 wet market centers in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjxIAAAAYAAJ |title=U.S. Trade and Prospects: Dairy, livestock, and poultry products |year=1992 |publisher=The Service |author=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service. Dairy, Livestock, and Poultry Division, United States. World Agricultural Outlook Board |page=3}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tekka Centre|Tekka Market]], [[Tiong Bahru#Tiong Bahru Market|Tiong Bahru Market]], and [[Chinatown, Singapore#Geography|Chinatown Complex Market]] are prominent wet markets containing seasonal fruit, fresh vegetables, imported beef, and live seafood.<ref name=\"cnn-sg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/singapore-wet-market/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |title=Singapore wet markets: Reminder of bygone days |date=22 June 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\nWet markets are the dominant preferred venue for grocery shopping in [[Thailand]] due to the local importance of fresh food.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-A-7d-2VpwcC |page=295 |title= Consumer Behavior and Culture: Consequences for Global Marketing and Advertising  |first=Marieke |last=de Mooij |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |year=2003|isbn=9780761926689 }}</ref>\n\n== Hygiene of wildlife markets ==\nIf [[sanitation]] standards are not maintained, wet markets containing wildlife products can spread [[disease|diseases]]. Because of the openness, newly introduced animals may come in direct contact with sales clerks, butchers, and customers. Insects such as [[flies]] have relatively easy access to the food products. The [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|avian flu]] and [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] outbreaks can be traced to keeping live animals in wet markets where the potential for zoonotic transmission is greatly increased.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/05/802938289/new-coronavirus-wont-be-the-last-outbreak-to-move-from-animal-to-human |title=New Coronavirus 'Won't Be the Last' Outbreak to Move from Animal to Human |department=Goats and Soda |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=2020-02-05 |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-01-24 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref> Wetmarkets were banned from carrying wildlife in Vietnam as a response.<ref name=\":1\" /> Chinese wet markets carrying wildlife had previously been closed in 2003 when they were implicated as playing a central part in the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], but had been reopened before being closed in 2020 again.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWet markets where animals are traded in unsanitary conditions combined with the ability of viruses to undergo fast recombination were pointed out by Chinese scientists as a \"time-bomb\" as early as in 2007.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=VC|date=Oct 2007|title=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=20|issue=4|pages=660\u201394|doi=10.1128/CMR.00023-07|pmid=17934078|pmc=2176051|quote=}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Large numbers and varieties of these wild game mammals in overcrowded cages and the lack of biosecurity measures in wet markets allowed the jumping of this novel virus from animals to human. (...) Coronaviruses are well known to undergo genetic recombination, which may lead to new genotypes and outbreaks. The presence of a large reservoir of SARS-CoV-like viruses in horseshoe bats, together with the culture of eating exotic mammals in southern China, is a time bomb.|author=VC Cheng|title=|source=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection}}\n\nAmidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese wet markets have been blamed for the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spinney|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/is-factory-farming-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Is factory farming to blame for coronavirus?|date=2020-03-28|work=The Observer|quote=Most of the attention so far has been focused on the interface between humans and the intermediate host, with fingers of blame being pointed at Chinese wet markets and eating habits,...|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Some reports say wildlife markets in other countries of Asia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/coronavirus-expert-shut-down-of-asias-wet-wildlife-markets-60-minutes/f7f7781f-8e44-4eb8-9704-804b1e1680ca|title=Coronavirus expert calls for shut down of Asia's wildlife markets|last=|first=|date=|website=Nine News Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5797739/wild-animals-markets-coronavirus/|title=Don't Blame China. The Next Pandemic Could Come From Anywhere|last=|first=|date=|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/africa-risks-virus-outbreak-from-wildlife-trade/|title=Africa Risks Virus Outbreak From Wildlife Trade|date=2020-02-28|website=WildAid|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymaverick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-02-a-sea-change-in-chinas-attitude-towards-wildlife-exploitation-may-just-save-the-planet/|title=A sea change in China's attitude towards wildlife exploitation may just save the planet|date=2020-03-02|newspaper=Daily Maverick|quote=Knights hoped China would also play a role to help \u201ccountries around the world. It\u2019s no good simply banning the trade in China. The same risks are very much out there in Asia as well as Africa.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"indiamongabay\">{{cite news|url=https://india.mongabay.com/2020/03/commentary-crackdown-on-wet-markets-and-illegal-wildlife-trade-could-prevent-the-next-pandemic/|title=Crackdown on wet markets and illegal wildlife trade could prevent the next pandemic|date=2020-03-25|newspaper=Mongabay India|quote=...what we do know is that wet markets such as Wuhan, and for that matter Agartala\u2019s Golbazar or the thousands such that exist in Asia and Africa allow for easy transmission of viruses and other pathogens from animals to humans.}}</ref> and in general all over the world are also similarly prone to health risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200326/fact-check-is-chinese-culture-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Fact-check: Is Chinese culture to blame for the coronavirus?|last=Mekelburg|first=Madlin|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> In April 2020, Anthony Fauci called for the international community to force the closure of wet markets due to the human-animal interface and potential for zoonotic diseases.<ref name=\"Fauci\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/anthony-fauci-foreign-wet-markets-shutdown-162975 |title='Shut down those things right away': Calls to close 'wet markets' ramp up pressure on China |first=Quint |last=Forgey |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\n<!-- This section is for content *about* media coverage of wet markets, not content *from* media coverage of wet markets -->\nIn [[Western media]], wet markets are often portrayed without distinguishing between general wet markets and wildlife markets, using montages images from different markets across China without specific identifying information.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\">{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last1=Lynteris|first1=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|date=2 March 2020|publisher=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|last=St. Cavendish|first=Christopher|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets|title=No, China's fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus|date=11 March 2020|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> These depictions have been criticized as exaggerated and [[Orientalism|Orientalist]], and have been blamed for fueling [[Sinophobia]] and \"Chinese otherness\".<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/><ref name=\"lat\"/><ref name=\"FP\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/coronavirus-covid19-dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-virus/ |publisher=[[Foreign Policy]] |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Coronavirus |last=Palmer |first=James |date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince the outbreak of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic, media reports urging for permanent blanket bans on all wet markets \u2013 as opposed to solely wildlife markets \u2013 have been criticized by some academics for undermining the epidemiological need to be specific about the particular species contained in the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market potentially at the origin of the pandemic.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Wet market in Tekka Centre, Singapore - 20030228.jpg|Wet market in Tekka Center, [[Singapore]]\nImage:HK SYP Market 60402.jpg|Indoor wet market in Hong Kong\nImage:E8975-Namdaemun-ginseng-and-matsutake-shop.jpg|Live turtles next to pickled ginseng in [[Namdaemun Market]], [[Seoul]]\nImage:Lok_fu_centre_wet_market.jpg|Indoor wet market under Lok Fu Shopping Centre in Hong Kong\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Artisanal food]]\n* [[Asian supermarket]]\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Farmers' market]]\n* [[Palengke]]\n* [[Pasar malam]]\n* [[Pasar pagi]]\n* [[Souk]]\n* [[Social distancing]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Wet markets}}\n{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/may/15/china-animalwelfare-cat | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Conservation (Environment), Wildlife (Environment), World news, China (News), Animal welfare (News), Food (impact of production on environment), Animals (News), Ethical and green living (Environment), Environment, Chinese food and drink, Asia Pacific (News) | date=15 May 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n[[Category:Food markets]]\n[[Category:Retail markets]]\n[[Category:Vegetables]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Market selling perishable goods, generally including meat or food animals}}\n{{Chinese|pic=WetmarketHK.jpg|picsize=250px|c=[[wiktionary:\u8857\u5e02|\u8857\u5e02]]|j=gaai<sup>1</sup> si<sup>5</sup>|l=street market|showflag=j|ci={{IPAc-yue|g|aai|1|.|s|i|5}}}}\n<!-- \"\u8857\u5e02\" only means \"wet market\" in Cantonese, so pinyin here is unnecessary -->\n\nA '''wet market''' (also called a '''public market''')<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/> is a [[marketplace]] selling fresh meat, fish, [[greengrocer|produce]], and other perishable goods as distinguished from \"dry markets\" that sell durable goods such as fabric and electronics.<ref>Wholesale Markets: Planning and Design Manual (Fao Agricultural Services Bulletin) (No 90)</ref><ref name=\"OED\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oed.com/view/Entry/227970 |title=wet, adj. |publisher=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |quote=wet market  n. South-East Asian a market for the sale of fresh meat, fish, and produce  |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Wet markets are common throughout the world.<ref name=\"nw\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/peta-launches-petition-close-wet-markets-coronavirus-1494803 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |title= PETA LAUNCHES PETITION TO SHUT DOWN LIVE ANIMAL MARKETS THAT BREED DISEASES LIKE COVID-19 |first=Khaleda |last=Rahman |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reardon|first=Thomas|last2=Timmer|first2=C. Peter|last3=Minten|first3=Bart|date=2012-07-31|title=Supermarket revolution in Asia and emerging development strategies to include small farmers|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=109|issue=31|pages=12332\u201312337|doi=10.1073/pnas.1003160108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3412023|pmid=21135250|bibcode=2012PNAS..10912332R}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800725826/why-wet-markets-are-the-perfect-place-to-spread-disease|title=Why Wet Markets Are The Perfect Place To Spread Disease|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Wet markets include a wide variety of markets, such as [[farmers' market]]s, [[fish market]]s, and [[Wildlife trade|wildlife market]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/>\n\nWet markets containing live animals, both domesticated and wild, as well as wildlife products have been linked to outbreaks of [[zoonotic disease]]s including [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\":2\" /> However, not all wet markets carry living animals or wildlife.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ZSCSH\" /> Wet markets were  banned from holding wildlife in China in 2003, including after the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], which was directly tied to such practices.<ref name=\":2\" /> Such regulations were lifted before being put into place again in 2020,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/74f1b26e-53c0-11ea-90ad-25e377c0ee1f|title=Coronavirus piles pressure on China\u2019s exotic animal trade|last=Yu|first=Sun|last2=Liu|first2=Xinning|date=2020-02-23|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> with other countries following suit.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eba067c4-69ce-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3|title=The economic case for ending wildlife trade hits home in Vietnam|last=Reed|first=John|date=2020-03-19|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nMedia reports that fail to distinguish between wet markets from those with live produce or wildlife have been blamed for fueling [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|xenophobia related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"FP\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/coronavirus-covid19-dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-virus/ |publisher=[[Foreign Policy]] |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Coronavirus |last=Palmer |first=James |date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe \"wet\" in \"wet market\" refers to the constantly wet floors as a consequence of the spraying of fresh produce and cleaning of meat and seafood stalls.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hiFxfmZteFgC |title=Cross-Cultural Marketing: Theory, Practice and Relevance |first=Dawn |last=Burton |page=146 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2008|isbn=9781134060177 }}</ref>\n\nAs early as 1948, \"wet market\" was identified as a name in English for a type of market.<ref name=\"IRCD\">{{cite web|url=https://northeastiowarcd.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IA-FM-Chapter-1.pdf |publisher=Northeast Iowa Resource Conservation & Development |title=Chapter 1: What is a Farmer's Market? |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> The term \"wet market\" originated from [[Hong Kong English]] and entered the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 May 2016 |title=East Asian words make it into ''Oxford English Dictionary'' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/13/east-asian-words-oxford-english-dictionary-hong-kong-singapore-oed |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date=22 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe term \"public market\" is synonymous with \"wet market\",<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/> although it may sometimes refer exclusively to state-owned and community-owned wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/><ref name=\"Morales-2009\"/>\n\n==Types of wet markets==\nThe term \"wet market\", which specifies markets that sell fresh produce and meat, include a broad variety of markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\">{{Cite journal |last=Zhong |first=Taiyang |last2=Si |first2=Zhenzhong |last3=Crush |first3=Jonathan |last4=Scott |first4=Steffanie |last5=Huang |first5=Xianjin |year=2019 |title=Achieving urban food security through a hybrid public-private food provisioning system: the case of Nanjing, China |journal=Food Security |language=en |volume=11 |issue=5 |pages=1071\u20131086 |doi=10.1007/s12571-019-00961-8 |issn=1876-4517}}</ref> Wet markets can be categorized according to their ownership structure ([[Privately held company|privately owned]], [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned]], or [[Community ownership|community-owned]]), scale ([[Wholesaling|wholesale]] or [[retail]]), and produce (vegetables, slaughtered meat, live animals).<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/> They can be further subcategorized based on whether the meat sold comes from [[Domestication of animals|domesticated]] or [[wildlife|wild animal]]s.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/>\n\n==Economy==\nWet markets are less dependent on imported goods than [[supermarket]]s due to their smaller volumes and lesser emphasis on consistency.<ref name=\"ATH-12\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=12}}</ref> Researchers have highlighted the lower prices, greater freshness of food, negotiation opportunities, and social interaction spaces as key reasons for the persistence of wet markets.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bougoure |first=Ursula |last2=Lee |first2=Bernard |year=2009 |editor-last=Lindgreen |editor-first=Adam |title=Service quality in Hong Kong: wet markets vs supermarkets |journal=British Food Journal |language=en |volume=111 |issue=1 |pages=70\u201379 |doi=10.1108/00070700910924245 |issn=0007-070X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Mele |first=Christopher |last2=Ng |first2=Megan |last3=Chim |first3=May Bo |year=2015 |title=Urban markets as a 'corrective' to advanced urbanism: The social space of wet markets in contemporary Singapore |journal=Urban Studies |language=en |volume=52 |issue=1 |pages=103\u2013120 |doi=10.1177/0042098014524613 |issn=0042-0980}}</ref>\n\nThe persistence of wet markets has been described as \"critical for ensuring urban [[food security]]\",<ref name=\"Morales-2009\">{{Cite journal |last=Morales |first=Alfonso |year=2009 |title=Public Markets as Community Development Tools |journal=Journal of Planning Education and Research |language=en |volume=28 |issue=4 |pages=426\u2013440 |doi=10.1177/0739456X08329471 |issn=0739-456X}}</ref><ref name=\"Morales-2011\">{{Cite journal |last=Morales |first=Alfonso |year=2011 |title=Marketplaces: Prospects for Social, Economic, and Political Development |journal=Journal of Planning Literature |language=en |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=3\u201317 |doi=10.1177/0885412210388040 |issn=0885-4122}}</ref> particularly in Chinese cities.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/> The influence of wet markets on urban food security include food pricing and physical accessibility.<ref name=\"ZSCSH\"/>\n\n==Wet markets by country==\n=== China ===\n[[File:Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market, Hall 1 (20190519152946).jpg|thumb|Seafood section of Sanqi Baihui Market in [[Beijing]], [[China]]]]\nThe origin of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in [[Wuhan]], [[China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/forefront/prevention-and-screening-articles/wuhan-coronavirus|title=COVID-19: What we know so far about the 2019 novel coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, proposals were made to ban the operation of wet markets selling wild animals for human consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-feb-17-2020-1.5466207/experts-call-for-global-ban-on-live-animal-markets-wildlife-trade-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak-1.5466219|title=Experts call for global ban on live animal markets, wildlife trade amidst coronavirus outbreak|date=February 17, 2020|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2020|title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak|author=Sarah Boseley}}</ref> A few others have pointed out that most wet markets in China do not sell wild animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radiichina.com/wet-markets-wild-animals-china/|title=No, You Won't Find \"Wild Animals\" in Most of China's Wet Markets|last=Bossons|first=Matthew|date=2020-02-25|website=RADII|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last=Lynteris|first=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market was shut down on 1 January 2020. The Chinese government subsequently announced a permanent ban on the sale of wild animal products at wet markets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/china-bans-wildlife-trade-consumption-coronavirus-2020-2|publisher=Business Insider|date=25 February 2020|title=China just banned the trade and consumption of wild animals. Experts think the coronavirus jumped from live animals to people at a market.|author=Aylin Woodward}}</ref> By {{date|2020-04-02|DMY}}, some temporarily closed wet markets in China were reported to have been reopened, leading to public criticism of the Chinese government's handling of wild animal trade by [[Anthony Fauci]] and [[Lindsey Graham]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'reilly|first=Andrew|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/lindsey-graham-asks-china-to-close-all-operating-wet-markets-after-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Lindsey Graham asks China to close 'all operating wet markets' after coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-04-02|work=Fox News|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowden|first=John|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/490834-graham-asks-colleagues-to-support-call-for-china-to-close-wet-markets|title=Graham asks colleagues to support call for China to close wet markets|date=2020-04-02|work=The Hill|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Fauci\"/>\n\n==== Hong Kong ====\n[[File:HK Bridges Street Market.JPG|thumb|The building that housed the former [[Bridges Street Market]] in [[Hong Kong]]]]\nIn 1920, the Reclamation Street Market was opened in [[Hong Kong]]. Due to structure problems, Reclamation Street Market was removed by the government in 1953.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5c46\u5eff\u4e00\u4e16\u7d00\u83ef\u4eba\u5730\u5340\u6b77\u53f2\u6559\u80b2\u8ad6\u6587\u96c6|trans-title=Second Collection of Historical Education Papers on Chinese in the 21st Century |author=Bao Shaolin|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (Hong Kong) Limited.|year=2012|language=Chinese|isbn=|location=|pages=332}}</ref> In 1957, Yau Ma Tei Street Market launched to replace the Reclamation Street Market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmis.hkpl.gov.hk/coverpage/-/coverpage/view?p_r_p_-1078056564_c=QF757YsWv59a9PNz3lScYjii24oro5jB&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_o=18&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_actual_q=%28%20%28%20allTermsMandatory%3A%28true%29%20OR+all_dc.title%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.creator%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.contributor%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.subject%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+fulltext%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20OR+all_dc.description%3A%28%E6%B2%B9%E9%BA%BB%E5%9C%B0%E8%A1%97%E5%B8%82%29%20%29%20%29&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_order=desc&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_sort_field=score&_coverpage_WAR_mmisportalportlet_log=Y|title=\u6cb9\u9ebb\u5730\u65b0\u5efa\u8857\u5e02\u6628\u6668\u958b\u5e55\u5f8c\u71df\u696d|trans-title=Yau Ma Tei New Market opened after opening yesterday morning|language=Chinese|last=|first=|date=1957-11-02|work=Hong Kong Business Daily|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> There were fixed-pitch stalls which sold vegetables, fruits, seafood, beef, pork, and poultry. Also, there were stalls selling baby chickens, baby ducks, and three-striped box turtles as pets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hkmemory.hk/collections/oral_history/All_Items_OH/oha_70/records/index.html|title=Yau Ma Tei's wet markets in the early post-war period|date=2011-03-29|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref><br />\n\nCentral Market was launched on 16 May 1842. Its position was central, on Queen's Road. In this market, people could find all kinds of meat, fruit and vegetables, poultry, salt fish, fresh fish, weighing rooms and money changers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1842/728468.pdf|title=The Friend Of China, and Hong Kong Gazette|date=1842-05-12|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn Hong Kong, wet markets are most frequented by older residents, those with lower incomes, and domestic helpers who serve approximately 10 percent of Hong Kong's residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/journals.htm?articleid=1412265&show=abstract |title=EmeraldInsight |website=EmeraldInsight.com |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Wet markets have become destinations for tourists to \"see the real Hong Kong\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/a-guide-to-hong-kongs-wet-markets/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Sei | last=Chong | title=A Guide to Hong Kong's Wet Markets | date=18 March 2011|accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref> Many of the wet market buildings are owned by property investment firms and as a result the price of food can vary from market to market.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elmer W. Cagape |url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/64501/expensive-food-tung-chung-hk/ |title=Tung Chung town pays the most for food in Hong Kong |work=Asian Correspondent |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, wet markets accounted for 70% of produce sales and 50% of meat sales in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"ATH-7\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urH_3knhcjAC&dq |title=Agricultural Trade Highlights |publisher=[[Foreign Agricultural Service]] |year=1994 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the government of Hong Kong proposed that all poultry should be slaughtered at central abattoirs to combat the spread of [[avian flu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.news.gov.hk/isd/ebulletin/en/category/issues/080614/html/080613en05005.htm |title=Central abattoir set for 2011 |website=Archive.news.gov.hk |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nHong Kong's wet markets use red lampshades to make the food look fresher.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u8d85\u5de8\u8857\u5e02\u71c8\u73fe\u8eab\u5546\u5834|trans-title=Super large wet market red lamps appears in shopping mall|url=http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|accessdate=19 November 2012|newspaper=Sharp Daily|date=14 September 2012|language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108070308/http://www.sharpdaily.hk/article/news/20120914/134111|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\n[[File:Mercado 20 de noviembre - Oaxaca de Ju\u00e1rez - 10.jpg|thumb|Fresh meat section of the Mercado 20 de Noviembre in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], [[Mexico]]]]\nSome traditional [[Mexico|Mexican]] open-air markets called ''[[tianguis]]'', such as the Mercado Margarita Maza de Ju\u00e1rez in [[Oaxaca City|Oaxaca]], are separated into a wet market (''zona h\u00fameda'') and a dry market (''zona seca'').<ref name=\"imparcial\">{{cite news |url=https://imparcialoaxaca.mx/oaxaca/304648/central-de-abasto-bomba-de-tiempo-y-nido-de-delincuencia/ |title=Central de Abasto: bomba de tiempo y nido de delincuencia |publisher=[[El Imparcial (Oaxaca)]] |date=9 May 2019 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singapore===\nIn the early 1990s, the slaughter of animals was banned in 12 inner-city markets and 22 wet market centers in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjxIAAAAYAAJ |title=U.S. Trade and Prospects: Dairy, livestock, and poultry products |year=1992 |publisher=The Service |author=United States. Foreign Agricultural Service. Dairy, Livestock, and Poultry Division, United States. World Agricultural Outlook Board |page=3}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tekka Centre|Tekka Market]], [[Tiong Bahru#Tiong Bahru Market|Tiong Bahru Market]], and [[Chinatown, Singapore#Geography|Chinatown Complex Market]] are prominent wet markets containing seasonal fruit, fresh vegetables, imported beef, and live seafood.<ref name=\"cnn-sg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/singapore-wet-market/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |title=Singapore wet markets: Reminder of bygone days |date=22 June 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\nWet markets are the dominant preferred venue for grocery shopping in [[Thailand]] due to the local importance of fresh food.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-A-7d-2VpwcC |page=295 |title= Consumer Behavior and Culture: Consequences for Global Marketing and Advertising  |first=Marieke |last=de Mooij |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |year=2003|isbn=9780761926689 }}</ref>\n\n== Hygiene of wildlife markets ==\nIf [[sanitation]] standards are not maintained, wet markets containing wildlife products can spread [[disease|diseases]]. Because of the openness, newly introduced animals may come in direct contact with sales clerks, butchers, and customers. Insects such as [[flies]] have relatively easy access to the food products. The [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|avian flu]] and [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] outbreaks can be traced to keeping live animals in wet markets where the potential for zoonotic transmission is greatly increased.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/05/802938289/new-coronavirus-wont-be-the-last-outbreak-to-move-from-animal-to-human |title=New Coronavirus 'Won't Be the Last' Outbreak to Move from Animal to Human |department=Goats and Soda |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=2020-02-05 |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/jan/24/calls-for-global-ban-wild-animal-markets-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |title=Calls for global ban on wild animal markets amid coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-01-24 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |accessdate=2020-02-29}}</ref> Wetmarkets were banned from carrying wildlife in Vietnam as a response.<ref name=\":1\" /> Chinese wet markets carrying wildlife had previously been closed in 2003 when they were implicated as playing a central part in the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]], but had been reopened before being closed in 2020 again.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWet markets where animals are traded in unsanitary conditions combined with the ability of viruses to undergo fast recombination were pointed out by Chinese scientists as a \"time-bomb\" as early as in 2007.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=VC|date=Oct 2007|title=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection|journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews|volume=20|issue=4|pages=660\u201394|doi=10.1128/CMR.00023-07|pmid=17934078|pmc=2176051|quote=}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Large numbers and varieties of these wild game mammals in overcrowded cages and the lack of biosecurity measures in wet markets allowed the jumping of this novel virus from animals to human. (...) Coronaviruses are well known to undergo genetic recombination, which may lead to new genotypes and outbreaks. The presence of a large reservoir of SARS-CoV-like viruses in horseshoe bats, together with the culture of eating exotic mammals in southern China, is a time bomb.|author=VC Cheng|title=|source=Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus as an Agent of Emerging and Reemerging Infection}}\n\nAmidst the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Chinese wet markets have been blamed for the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spinney|first=Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/28/is-factory-farming-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Is factory farming to blame for coronavirus?|date=2020-03-28|work=The Observer|quote=Most of the attention so far has been focused on the interface between humans and the intermediate host, with fingers of blame being pointed at Chinese wet markets and eating habits,...|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Some reports say wildlife markets in other countries of Asia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/china-could-end-global-trade-wildlife|title=China Could End the Global Trade in Wildlife|date=2020-03-26|website=Sierra Club|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/coronavirus-expert-shut-down-of-asias-wet-wildlife-markets-60-minutes/f7f7781f-8e44-4eb8-9704-804b1e1680ca|title=Coronavirus expert calls for shut down of Asia's wildlife markets|last=|first=|date=|website=Nine News Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5797739/wild-animals-markets-coronavirus/|title=Don't Blame China. The Next Pandemic Could Come From Anywhere|last=|first=|date=|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildaid.org/africa-risks-virus-outbreak-from-wildlife-trade/|title=Africa Risks Virus Outbreak From Wildlife Trade|date=2020-02-28|website=WildAid|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymaverick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-02-a-sea-change-in-chinas-attitude-towards-wildlife-exploitation-may-just-save-the-planet/|title=A sea change in China's attitude towards wildlife exploitation may just save the planet|date=2020-03-02|newspaper=Daily Maverick|quote=Knights hoped China would also play a role to help \u201ccountries around the world. It\u2019s no good simply banning the trade in China. The same risks are very much out there in Asia as well as Africa.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"indiamongabay\">{{cite news|url=https://india.mongabay.com/2020/03/commentary-crackdown-on-wet-markets-and-illegal-wildlife-trade-could-prevent-the-next-pandemic/|title=Crackdown on wet markets and illegal wildlife trade could prevent the next pandemic|date=2020-03-25|newspaper=Mongabay India|quote=...what we do know is that wet markets such as Wuhan, and for that matter Agartala\u2019s Golbazar or the thousands such that exist in Asia and Africa allow for easy transmission of viruses and other pathogens from animals to humans.}}</ref> and in general all over the world are also similarly prone to health risks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200326/fact-check-is-chinese-culture-to-blame-for-coronavirus|title=Fact-check: Is Chinese culture to blame for the coronavirus?|last=Mekelburg|first=Madlin|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> In April 2020, Anthony Fauci called for the international community to force the closure of wet markets due to the human-animal interface and potential for zoonotic diseases.<ref name=\"Fauci\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/anthony-fauci-foreign-wet-markets-shutdown-162975 |title='Shut down those things right away': Calls to close 'wet markets' ramp up pressure on China |first=Quint |last=Forgey |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\n<!-- This section is for content *about* media coverage of wet markets, not content *from* media coverage of wet markets -->\nIn [[Western media]], wet markets are often portrayed without distinguishing between general wet markets and wildlife markets, using montages images from different markets across China without specific identifying information.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\">{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/why-shutting-down-chinese-wet-markets-could-be-a-terrible-mistake-130625|title=Why shutting down Chinese 'wet markets' could be a terrible mistake|last1=Lynteris|first1=Christos|last2=Fearnley|first2=Lyle|date=2 March 2020|publisher=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news|last=St. Cavendish|first=Christopher|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/story/2020-03-11/coronavirus-china-wet-markets|title=No, China's fresh food markets did not cause coronavirus|date=11 March 2020|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> These depictions have been criticized as exaggerated and [[Orientalism|Orientalist]], and have been blamed for fueling [[Sinophobia]] and \"Chinese otherness\".<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/><ref name=\"lat\"/><ref name=\"FP\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/27/coronavirus-covid19-dont-blame-bat-soup-for-the-virus/ |publisher=[[Foreign Policy]] |title=Don't Blame Bat Soup for the Coronavirus |last=Palmer |first=James |date=27 January 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince the outbreak of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic, media reports urging for permanent blanket bans on all wet markets \u2013 as opposed to solely wildlife markets \u2013 have been criticized by some academics for undermining the epidemiological need to be specific about the particular species contained in the Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market potentially at the origin of the pandemic.<ref name=\"lynteris-fearnley\"/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Wet market in Tekka Centre, Singapore - 20030228.jpg|Wet market in Tekka Center, [[Singapore]]\nImage:HK SYP Market 60402.jpg|Indoor wet market in Hong Kong\nImage:E8975-Namdaemun-ginseng-and-matsutake-shop.jpg|Live turtles next to pickled ginseng in [[Namdaemun Market]], [[Seoul]]\nImage:Lok_fu_centre_wet_market.jpg|Indoor wet market under Lok Fu Shopping Centre in Hong Kong\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Artisanal food]]\n* [[Asian supermarket]]\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Farmers' market]]\n* [[Palengke]]\n* [[Pasar malam]]\n* [[Pasar pagi]]\n* [[Souk]]\n* [[Social distancing]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Externa